item.title: Former Pemex CEO's Allegations Rock Mexico's Political Class
item.description: Allegations made by Emilio Lozoya, a disgraced former chief executive of Mexico’s state-run oil giant Petróleos Mexicanos, rock the country’s political class and add fuel to the widest-reaching corruption probe in Mexico’s modern history.

item.title: Iraq's Kadhimi, Trump Sidestep Setting Deadline for Withdrawing U.S. Troops From Iraq
item.description: Iraq’s new prime minister held his first meeting with President Trump, as their two countries grapple with the threat posed by remnants of Islamic State, Iran’s influence in the region and plans for reducing the level of American troops in Iraq.

item.title: Putin Rival Alexei Navalny in Critical Condition After Suspected Poisoning
item.description: Russian opposition politician Alexei Navalny, a critic of President Vladimir Putin and Moscow’s political elite, was admitted to an intensive-care unit after a suspected poisoning left him unconscious, his spokeswoman said.

item.title: Extended Montreal Dock Workers' Walkout Rattles Canadian Supply Chains
item.description: A strike at Canada’s second-busiest port is showing few signs of progress deep into the second week of the walkout, as concerns rise about the damage an extended shutdown could do to the Canadian economy.

item.title: Possible F-35 Jet Sale to U.A.E. Puts Israel in Bind
item.description: Talks between the U.S. and the United Arab Emirates on a potential sale of advanced F-35 jets are raising thorny questions for Israel’s security in the Middle East.

item.title: Iran Unveils New Missiles, Improving Its Reach at Sea and to Israel
item.description: The display of new missiles adds to a buildup of regional animosity after the U.A.E. and Israel last week said they were forging diplomatic relations.

item.title: Islamist Attacks in Mozambique Threaten to Disrupt Total-Led Natural-Gas Project
item.description: Fighting between Islamic extremist rebels and Mozambique’s army over a key port is threatening to disrupt the East African nation’s burgeoning natural-gas developments, including a multibillion-dollar project led by French energy giant Total.

item.title: Battered Eurozone Could See More Stimulus in the Fall
item.description: European Central Bank officials signaled that they could roll out new monetary stimulus to shore up economic growth.
